===Etymology===
{{IPAchar|/opoki/}} → {{IPAchar|/oɸoki/}} → {{IPAchar|/oɸokiki/}} → {{IPAchar|/owokiː/}} → {{IPAchar|/oːkiː/}}

Appears in the {{w|Muromachi period}}, 1337 to 1573 {{CE}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

From older adjective {{ja-r|大き|おおき|pos=ancient reading ''opoki''}}, derived as the attributive form ''ōki'' (ancient ''opoki'') of cognate adjective ''ōshi'' (ancient ''oposi''; attributive ''opoki'' appearing already in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' of 759 {{CE}},<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|3|339}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man3Yos.html#339 here]</ref> meaning both “large” or “many”, spelled as {{ja-r|多し|おおし}} or {{ja-r|大し|おおし}}, modern {{cog|ja|-}} {{ja-r|多い|おおい|many}}), in turn derived from {{der|ja|ojp|sort=おおきい|-}} adjective ''opo'' (“indistinct; of uncertain size, shape, or amount”; read as ''ō'' in modern {{cog|ja|-}}, spelled as {{ja-l|凡}} or {{ja-l|大}}).<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

